==English==

===Etymology===
A word from Middle English, of Germanic origin, borrowed via Old French (see '''[[sénéchal]]''').

===Noun===
'''seneschal''' (''plural:'' '''seneschaux''' or '''seneschals''')
#A [[steward]] in charge of a [[medieval]] [[nobleman]]'s [[estate]]. See Wikipedia's article on the [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seneschal seneschaux].